1108–circa 1129","1108–1129":"1108–1129","1108–Female":"1108–Overleden","1127–Male":"1127–Overleden","1128–1219":"1128–1219","1075–1161":"1075–1161","1080–1165":"1080–1165","1080":"1080","1165":"1165","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","1129":"1129","1128":"1128","abt 1127":"circa 1127","1127":"1127","about 1129":"circa 1129","about 1108":"circa 1108","about 1127":"circa 1127","about 1128":"circa 1128","1219":"1219","1108":"1108","Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","of Ellenhall, Staffs., Eng.":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ellenhall Manor, Raunton, Staffordshire":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1108–about 1129":"about 1108–about 1129","1108–1129":"1108–1129","1108–Female":"1108–Deceased","1127–Male":"1127–Deceased","1128–1219":"1128–1219","1075–1161":"1075–1161","1080–1165":"1080–1165","1080":"1080","1165":"1165","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","1129":"1129","1128":"1128","abt 1127":"about 1127","1127":"1127","about 1129":"about 1129","about 1108":"about 1108","about 1127":"about 1127","about 1128":"about 1128","1219":"1219","1108":"1108","Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","of Ellenhall, Staffs., Eng.":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Ellenhall Manor, Raunton, Staffordshire":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Noel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Pierre, Normand, Antoine, Jacques, Alphonse, Leonce, Lucien, Marcel, Damien, Emile, Francois.","French and Walloon (<b>Noël</b>); English: from the Old French personal name <i>Noël</i>, Middle English <i>Noel</i>, from Old French <i>no(u)el</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis (dies)</i> ‘birthday’), used for someone born during the Christmas period. Alternatively, a nickname for someone who had some special connection with the Christmas season, such as owing the particular feudal duty of providing a yule-log to the lord of the manor, or having given a memorable performance as the Lord of Misrule. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium. Compare   Christmas   and   Newell  .","English: sometimes a post-medieval variant of <b>Knowle</b> and   Knoll   (see   Knowles  ). The loss of /k/ before /n/ is known in everyday speech by the 17th century and may have been earlier."],"variants":[{"name":"Nowell","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Noel  ,   Knowles  , or   Newell  ."]},{"name":"Christmas","meanings":["English (southeastern): nickname from Middle English <i>Criste(s)masse</i>, <i>-messe</i> ‘Christmas Day’, also ‘the Christmas season’, perhaps for someone who was born at Christmas or one who played the part of the King of Christmas in Yuletide games. The name was also established in County Waterford, Ireland, in 1622.","Americanized form (translation into English) of French <b>Noël</b> (see   Noel  )."]},{"name":"Nadal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Miguel, Francisco, Jose, Luis, Caridad, Digna, Jaime, Juan, Juan Carlos, Manuel, Otilio.","Catalan and French (Occitan): from the personal name <i>Nadal</i>, from <i>nadal</i> ‘Christmas’ (from Latin <i>natalis</i> ‘birthday’), the name given to a child born on that day or during that time of year. Compare   Noel  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Noel was born about 1108, in Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England, his father, Count Robert I Valognes, was 35 and his mother, Countess Agnes de Lacy, was 29. He married Celestria de Limesi about 1127, in Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1129, in his hometown, at the age of 23."},"et":{"about 1108–about 1129":"umbes 1108–umbes 1129","1108–1129":"1108–1129","1108–Female":"1108–Surnud","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1128–1219":"1128–1219","1075–1161":"1075–1161","1080–1165":"1080–1165","1080":"1080","1165":"1165","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","1129":"1129","1128":"1128","abt 1127":"umbes 1127","1127":"1127","about 1129":"umbes 1129","about 1108":"umbes 1108","about 1127":"umbes 1127","about 1128":"umbes 1128","1219":"1219","1108":"1108","Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","of Ellenhall, Staffs., Eng.":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ellenhall Manor, Raunton, Staffordshire":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1108–about 1129":"noin 1108–noin 1129","11